<HEAD>
<TITLE>About Issues 96 -- Heritage</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Issues '96: The Candidate's Briefing Book</h2>
<b><A HREF="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a></b>
<p>
<h3>ABOUT ISSUES `96</h3>
</center><P>
<P><I>Issues `96</I> is intended as a handbook for conservative candidates 
of all parties seeking national office.
<P>
<P><I>Issues `96</I> is broken down into sections, one dealing with 
domestic issues likely to be part of the debate, and the other dealing 
with foreign policy and defense issues. Each section begins with a 
general introduction.
<P>
<P>Each chapter follows a general structure (with some variation 
in the foreign policy section). The chapter first summarizes the 
principal issues considered likely to be raised during the election. 
The main body of the chapter then provides candidate-friendly 
statistics and other information to help frame the debate. Following 
this is a summary of the record of the 104th Congress and the 
Clinton Administration on the issue, and a set of policy 
recommendations for 1997. Finally, chapters include a question-and-answer 
section dealing with questions likely to be raised during the debate. 
The information in each chapter is fully footnoted for reference, and 
a list of experts and relevant Heritage publications is included.
<P>
<P>The material in each chapter is as up-to-date as possible. 
<I>Issues `96</I> went into final production in mid-February; whenever 
possible, policy developments since that time have been noted. Updates 
will be issued if there are developments that affect key parts of a 
chapter. These updates can be obtained from The Heritage 
Foundation Government Relations Department or through the 
Heritage Internet home page.
<P>
<P><I>Issues `96</I>, chapter updates, and all other Heritage 
Foundation studies are available on the Internet through the Town Hall 
site (<a href="http://www.townhall.com">http://www.townhall.com</a>) or directly through Heritage's home page (<a href="/heritage">http://www.heritage.org</a>). The Town Hall site provides 
information and publications from many leading conservative 
organizations, including <a href="/heritage">Heritage</a>, <a href="/atr/1.html">Americans for Tax Reform</a>, <a href="/empower">Empower America</a>, <a href="/townhall/FRC">The Family Research Council</a>, and <a href="/nationalreview"><I>National Review</I></a>. 
<P>
<P>To retrieve articles and publications from Heritage via 
Internet, simply access the Heritage site, click on the link for the 
<a href="/heritage/library">Publications Library</a>, and choose the policy area of interest. Areas 
covered are Budget and Taxation, Crime and Law, Economics, 
Education, Environment, Family and Culture, Health and Welfare, 
Regulation, and Foreign Policy. The Town Hall site also permits you 
to conduct <a href="/index/improved">full text searches</a> of all Heritage Foundation 
documents, and of all documents in the sites of other Town Hall groups.
<P>
<P>In addition, <a href="/heritage/cd_ranking/i-cdrank.html"><I>The Congressional District Ranking Book</I></a> is available from the Heritage home page. This presents over 100 tables 
of demographic data broken down by congressional district, an 
extremely useful reference tool for candidates.
<P>
<P>To receive publications directly from The Heritage 
Foundation Government Relations department via fax, contact <a href="mailto: reedk@heritage.org">Kristie Reed</a> 
at 202-546-4400. <I>Issues `96</I> chapters and a number of other 
Heritage studies also are available in the Adobe Acrobat portable 
document format. These can be transmitted via internet e-mail. Using 
the Acrobat Reader software, <a href="http://www.adobe.com/acrobat/readstep.html">available free</a> of charge from the 
Adobe home page (<a href="http://www.adobe.com">http://www.adobe.com</a>), the files can be read 
and printed from any personal computer. Publications in the 
Acrobat format can be searched by keyword and topic.
<P>
