<HEAD>
<TITLE>Labor, Employment, and Wages -- Issues 96 -- Heritage</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Issues '96: The Candidate's Briefing Book</h2>
<b><A HREF="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a></b>
</center><p>
<h3>Chapter 5</h3>
<center><h2>
LABOR, EMPLOYMENT,AND WAGES
</H2>
<CITE><b>By <a href="/heritage/staff/wilson.htm">D. Mark Wilson</a></b>
</CITE>
<p>
<P><A HREF="chpt5.html#ISSUES">The Issues</A> | <A HREF="chpt5.html#FACTS">The Facts</A> |  <A HREF="chpt5.html#RECORD">The Record</A> | <A HREF="chpt5.html#Q&A">Q&amp;A</A> | <a href="chpt5.html#EXP">Experts</a> 
</center>
<p>
<a href="labor_m1.gif">Map 1</a>: Payroll Job Growth Since Recession, 1991-1995<br>
<a href="labor_m2.gif">Map 2</a>: Growth in Real Annual Pay: 1978-1994<br>
<a href="labor_1.gif">Chart 1</a>: Percent Change in Real Hourly Earnings: 1973-1994<br>
<a href="labor_2.gif">Chart 2</a>: Productivity and Real Compensation Per Hour Continue to Increase<br>
<a href="labor_3.gif">Chart 3</a>: Income Mobility: More Americans Moving Up, Not Down<br> 
<a href="labor_4.gif">Chart 4</a>: Pre-, Post- OSHA Work-Related Fatality Rate<br>
<a href="labor_5.gif">Chart 5</a>: Workplace Injuries<br>  
<p>
<B><A NAME="ISSUES">THE ISSUES
</A></B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>American labor law is largely a product of the conditions and  perspectives
of the 1930s. It needs to be reformed. Today's  economy, labor market, and
labor-management relations are very  different from the time when most of
America's major labor laws  were passed. Instead of modernizing labor law in
recent years,  however, the federal government has continued to place more 
regulations, mandates, and taxes on employers and workers. The result:  fewer
job opportunities and slower real wage growth.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Over the past 25 years, the United States has moved from a  manufacturing to
a global service economy, competition has  increased, and more American women
are working than ever before.  Workers are demanding more flexible hours,
working conditions,  compensation packages, and workplace involvement than
current laws  and regulations allow. Employers are straining under 
unnecessarily burdensome regulations, mandates, lawsuits, and taxes. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P> Reform of America's labor laws is long overdue. The  primary objectives of
this reform should be to:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Reduce</B> excessive burdens on businesses, job
opportunities,  and real wage growth while maintaining workplace health and
safety;
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 2 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Improve</B> labor-market flexibility while maintaining basic  employment
protections; and 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Strengthen</B> and expand workers' rights to work at home, to join  or
not join unions, and to form employee-employer committees  to improve
productivity, quality, and customer service.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Fundamental changes that focus on these objectives would  free workers and
employers to create a family-friendly labor  market, increase productivity, and
improve real wage growth. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Reforming the administration and enforcement of America's  archaic labor
laws, moreover, could save taxpayers $10.5  billion over five years.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#1">1</A>  This could be accomplished by
closing the  Department of Labor as a Cabinet-level department and moving 
certain of its key national functions into sub-Cabinet agencies or  other
departments. Other functions that are not national in scope  should be devolved
to the states, or in some cases to the private  sector. Obsolete, ineffective,
and wasteful rules and programs should  be repealed or closed down.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In 1992 the main issue was the economy. Specifically, it was  the jobless
recovery that resulted from President Bush's tax and  regulatory increases.
Although job security continues to concern  many workers, since the end of the
recession the resilient  American economy has created over 8 million jobs and
the major labor  issues have shifted to wage growth and income inequality. The 
idea that workers are falling down the economic ladder and no  longer can afford
to raise families has become conventional wisdom.  The debate also has developed
a disturbing class warfare tone  that clouds the issue and unnecessarily
polarizes Americans. 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 3 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P> Conservative candidates need to deal with these issues  head-on. They must
reject class warfare arguments as economic  nonsense. And to the extent that
real wages are falling for some  workers, candidates must point out that the
solution is not higher  taxes, more mandates, or job-killing increases in the
minimum  wage. Instead, what is needed are lower taxes for families and  reforms
that will increase worker productivity and job opportunities  for Americans
through such things as improving basic education  and encouraging more
investment. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="FACTS">THE FACTS</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Obsolete Laws
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>America's economy, labor market conditions, and  labor-management relations
have changed since most of the country's  major labor laws were passed. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>-     Congress enacted the Davis-Bacon Act in 1931, 
unemployment insurance and the employment service in 1935, the National  Labor
Relations Act in 1935, the Fair Labor Standards Act in 1938,  and the Labor
Management Relations Act in 1947. Even the  Occupational Safety and Health Act
was passed a quarter century ago,  in 1970. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Women now account for over 45 percent of the labor force,  up from 29
percent in 1950. The labor force participation rate  for married mothers with
children under 6 years of age has  increased from 11 percent in 1950 to over 47
percent today. 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 4 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Manufacturing now accounts for 16.4 percent of all jobs,  compared
with 33.7 percent in 1950. Unions now represent only  15.5 percent of workers,
down from 35.5 percent in 1945. Exports  have increased from 3.8 percent of
gross domestic product (GDP)  in 1950 to 11.6 percent in 1993, and imports have
increased from  3.2 percent to 12.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Two recent national polls revealed that 65 percent of  Americans favor
changes in labor law that would allow for more flexible  work schedules and 58
percent would choose paid time off more  often than overtime wages; 63 percent
of workers prefer  employer-employee cooperative committees over unions or labor
 laws.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#2">2</A>  
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Impact of Regulations, Mandates, and Taxes</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Federal regulations, mandates, and taxes have slowed  productivity and real
wage growth, and have limited job opportunities.  Since 1970, the expansion of
federally mandated benefits and  worker protections has taken a heavy toll.
Several studies point to the  job-destroying effect of the regulatory and
mandate explosion in  recent years.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#3">3</A>
 For example:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>-     There are at least three million fewer jobs in the 
American economy today because of the growth of regulations over the  last 20
years.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#5">4</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     A 1990 study estimated that environmental regulations alone  had
caused national employment to be 1.2 percent less in 1990 than  it otherwise
would have been.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#5">5</A>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>With each Congress, Washington has placed tougher  requirements 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 5 -->  and restrictions on employers and
the labor  market.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#6">6</A>  Although
current workplace policies and regulations are well  intentioned, their benefits
are outweighed by their negative consequences  for both workers and employers.
Further, the growing regulatory  burden has made federal workplace inspectors as
feared as IRS  auditors, and most businesses very cautious about hiring 
additional workers. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>-     In 1994, legally required benefits<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#7">7</A> accounted for 8.9 percent  of total
employer payrolls, up from 6.3 percent in 1971 and 3.5  percent in 1951.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#8">8</A>  These mandated benefits are not &quot;free&quot;
to  the worker, as many employees assume. A range of studies  indicates that, on
average, the cost of 88 percent of all legally required  benefits or payroll is
shifted to workers in the form of reduced  cash compensation.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#9">9</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Mandated requirements, such as family and medical leave, add  to the
cost of hiring and managing workers and directly affect  an employer's decisions
about whether and when to hire a  worker, which worker to hire, how much cash to
pay the worker, and  how long to keep that worker. The rise in nonwage labor
costs is one  of the most important forces leading employers to lay off workers,
 as well as to utilize part-time, temporary, and contract  labor.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#10">10</A> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-    The increase in mandated benefits does not include the cost to 
employers and workers of complying with workplace safety  and health
regulations.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#11">11</A>  One study has
estimated that 19 percent  of the productivity slowdown during the 1970s is
directly  attributable to regulations published by the Occupational Safety and 
Health Administration (OSHA).<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#12">12</A> 
Further, since productivity and  workers' pay and benefits rise together, OSHA
regulations are  directly 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 6 -->  responsible for some part of the
slowdown in wage growth.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Tax Increases.</B> Since the end of the last recession in March  1991,
employment has increased by  8.3 million to 125.1 million, and  the unemployment
rate has declined 1.2 percentage points to 5.6  percent.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#13">13</A>  Compared with past recoveries,
however, the  U.S. economy is performing below expected  levels.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#14">14</A>  Whereas employment growth in
previous post-war recoveries averaged  12.9 percent 55 months after the end of a
recession, employment in  the current recovery has grown only 7.2 percent over a
similar  period of time. One factor that aided employment growth in  recoveries
during the 1960s and 1980s was a reduction in tax rates. But  the Bush/Clinton
tax increases of 1990 and 1993, which burdened  a stalling economy, have limited
job growth significantly  since 1991.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#15">15</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>*     In the early 1980s, a faster growing economy enabled more
 Americans to participate in the labor force. After growing 2.4  percentage
points from November 1982 to November 1989, the labor  force participation rate
has not improved.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>*     The percentage of employed Americans increased from 57.3  percent in
November 1982 to 63.1 percent in March 1990. Since  then, the
employment-population ratio, like the labor force  participation rate, has not
improved.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>EMPLOYMENT GROWTH LOW-TAX VS. HIGH-TAX ECONOMIC EXPANSIONS</B>
</P>
<P></P>
<TABLE><TR><TD COLSTART="1">       (in thousands)</TD><TD COLSTART="2">     
Reagan Expansion </TD><TD COLSTART="3">         Bush/Clinton Expansion</TD></TR><TR
><TD COLSTART="1"></TD><TD COLSTART="2">          (11/82 to 5/87)</TD><TD
COLSTART="3">               (3/91 to 9/95)</TD></TR><TR><TD COLSTART="1">Total
Employment</TD><TD COLSTART="2">+13,322</TD><TD COLSTART="3"> +8,349
</TD></TR><TR><TD COLSTART="1">Labor Force Participation Rate</TD><TD
COLSTART="2">+1.5 points </TD><TD COLSTART="3">+0.2 points
</TD></TR><TR><TD COLSTART="1">Employment Population Ratio</TD><TD
COLSTART="2">+4.3 points </TD><TD COLSTART="3">+1.2 points</TD></TR><TR><TD
COLSTART="1">Self-Employed</TD><TD COLSTART="2">+802</TD><TD COLSTART="3">+109
</TD></TR><TR><TD COLSTART="1">Full-Time Employment
</TD><TD COLSTART="2">+12,305
</TD><TD COLSTART="3">+5,089</TD></TR><TR><TD COLSTART="1">Total Payroll Jobs</TD>
<TD COLSTART="2">+12,915</TD><TD COLSTART="3">+8,612</TD></TR><TR><TD
